* On the Versace-Prada sitch: The news from the Bloomberg terminal this mor=
ning suggests that Prada has hired Citi to take a look at Versace, adding a=
nother potential acquirer to the list. In yesterday=E2=80=99s Inner Circle =
email=E2=80=94upgrade to if you haven=E2=80=99t already ( https://puck.news=
/newsletter_content/an-hermes-surprise-versace-dark-horses/?utm_campaign=3D=
Line+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F10%2F25%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%281%2F10%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=E2=80=94I noted that market sources (a.k.a=
=2E bankers) were speculating about two other
potential buyers: the Agnelli family holdco, Exor, and some sort of Kering-=
Mayhoola mashup. But this Prada idea is potentially the most sound. Our bes=
t analyst guy, Luca Solca, told Reuters he thought it wasn=E2=80=99t a terr=
ible idea, especially because the two brands cater to different consumer gr=
oups. Prada is cerebral, Versace is flashy, both are fabulous.=C2=A0
=C2=A0While never as bad off as Versace is now, Prada implemented an incred=
ible turnaround
over the past seven years or so that included making over its merchandising=
 and distribution strategy. Prada is better than anyone at taking the geniu=
s of the runway and making it feel commercial. That said, the Bertelli fami=
ly has tried in the past to manage other big fashion brands and failed. In =
the late =E2=80=9990s, early-2000s, of course, patriarch Patrizio Bertelli =
attempted to build a competitor to LVMH and what was then known as the Gucc=
i Group, now Kering. It
didn=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0

However, it=E2=80=99s Bertelli=E2=80=99s son, Lorenzo, who would be operati=
ng this into the future. There is currently a transitional, effective C.E.O=
=2E who has been managing the succes=
sion gap years. There=E2=80=99s also a ru=
mored change on the creative side of Versace that indicates the speculation=
 about the Prada Group could be very real. More on Monday.

Sarah Shapiro
Sarah Shapiro

* All brands go to heaven: Earlier this week, it was announced that JCPenne=
y had combined forces with SPARC Group=E2=80=94which licenses some of Authe=
ntic Brands Group=E2=80=99s post-prime mall brands, namely A=C3=A9ropostale=
, Brooks Brothers, Eddie Bauer, Lucky, and Nautica=E2=80=94to create retail=
